text: This brought me to tears ‚Äî God really does do miracles. My senior year of high school I went through a super rough time and almost tried taking my own life. At the exact moment that I went to do it, after praying for a sign and a reason to keep on going, my best friend FaceTimed me to tell me she loved me and give me a good God talk that prompted me to going into intensive therapy. My whole church was there with me, praying for me to help me get through my depression and anxiety. My friend later told me she just had a calling in her heart to call me right then that night and I believe that was God giving me my sign and telling me to hold on because things will get better with him. And they did. God doesn‚Äôt let bad things happen to us ‚Äî we live in a world run by Satan and the bad things that happen are satan‚Äôs doing. All we can do is pray and surrender and know that God is great and he will help us come out the other side of the fire, unscathed. Even when we feel as if we‚Äôre burning, God is making us knew. I‚Äôm excited for this movie and can‚Äôt wait to see another way God has preformed a true miracle

text: This was NOT a "miracle". Children have been in extreme hypothermia before for as many minutes and survived. Is it pretty amazing? Yes. But not a "miracle". A "miracle" would have been if he had his head chopped off while in the frozen water and his head floated to his hands and he reattached it back to his body, then became conscious and was completely healthy. A miracle is supposed to be something impossibly, extraordinary that science can't begin to explain. Freezing people to later animate them again has been theorized and experimented on for decades. It's not new or miraculous. Now, if people need to believe in this, then let them if it gets them through the day. Some people need religion to cope with their lives. As long as they don't tell me I'm wrong for not believing the same thing- then have at it Hos.

text: I‚Äôm sorry. I‚Äôm Jewish. Are you all gonna make hateful religious comments towards me now? I don‚Äôt believe in religious movies and their messages. At least not all the time. But considering the fact that this movie is based off a true story, you all should be ashamed of yourselves for putting other beliefs and religions down. So what? This mother just so happened to pray for her sons life and her son just so happened to survive. Sure, some of you might say this is God‚Äôs doing, while some of you might say this was a miracle or that it was just a coincidence that this boy managed to live. With that said, whatever you believe feel free to say it. Unless however you are just going to put down everybody else for what they believe, than you can just keep it to yourself. Every religion has a purpose and reason. And yes that does include Atheism. Atheism might not be considered a religion by most people because atheists don‚Äôt believe in god, but they do still have beliefs. What I‚Äôm trying to say here, is that we all have different beliefs and I personally think that all of them should be accepted. I also think this movie might say something about that. Now please if you are going to comment anything can you at least make it a nice comment? And NOT attack others about their comments? And now I will ask of you all to please wait until this movie comes out and keep your hateful comments to yourself. Nobody wants to hear them. Most of you talk about how we as a race need to be accepting of other religions, genders, sexuality‚Äôs, etc. but when you make comments that are hateful against any of those things, you aren‚Äôt doing what you‚Äôre preaching. So please, fix your own hate and ignorance before saying anything. Religion is whatever you make of it. So don‚Äôt make it into something that‚Äôs going to turn people against each other. Thank you for reading all of this if you have. And for those of you who are going to write a hateful comment about the things I said (because I know somebody will) I‚Äôd like to thank you in advance. I highly appreciate the criticism. I‚Äôm sure I need some criticism in my life just like you do. (and no I‚Äôm not a hippy so you can‚Äôt make a hateful comment about that either). I hope you all take what I said into consideration and hopefully you‚Äôll actually listen to it. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚úåÔ∏è

text: These sorts of films really get me. I'm a firm agnostic, leaning heavily towards atheism so i can't help but find these stories a little ridiculous. Which is not to say i have a problem with religion or that i think other people shouldn't believe, in fact often i think it's a great comfort to people, but i have a hard time getting fully into a plot like this. I like the idea of faith though. Who knows if that boy survived because of God or just a really healthy body. But whilst i think it's a little silly, i also think it's wonderful that people can have that amount of faith. If that makes sense. In any case, this looks like it'll be a great film for those days when you just want to have a good cry.

text: The saying "they're not dead til they are warm and dead" has been known by first responders for decades. God didn't save this kid, biology and luck did. The body does everything slower when it is cold, including dying. Had he gone under in warmer water, his brain would have been starved of oxygen and decayed within 5 minutes, but because the water was cold the tissue in his brain and other organs was preserved for longer. It's all science, the very same science that conclusively proves evolution.

text: Can we all say "fundamentalist religious crap?" How do they know it was their god that saved the kid? Maybe it was Satan? Or Ishtar? Or Ganesh? Or Shiva? Or Thor (he at least has a history of actually saving people)? Or just freak combination of genetics and circumstances? Oh no--can't have that: it must be a divine miracle. Would they still be calling it that if he came back severely brain-damaged? or partially paralyzed? Or a psychopath? Or a brain-damaged paralyzed psychopath? This looks like the sort of feel-good crap that belongs on the Hallmark channel. Or the Lifetime channel. Certainly not something I'd want to actually waste perfectly good $ on. Hell, I'd rather pay to see Last Jedi, or an M Night Shamalan marathon, even knowing that it is terrible.

text: Attention!   If you have gone through losing someone you love, child, mother, father. And have bad experiences in the hospital, DO NOT WATCH THIS. Yes, it's a very powerful and very amazing movie, but it does trigger certain events.   Like me, I grew up with my mother being in the hospital. I've watched them do things to my mother and almost have my mother die right in front of me. (I lost her 3 years ago). It brought it back so hard, I had to leave the room, sobbing my eyes out.   It was still an amazing movie, and really does question your faith in God at the end. I got from this movie, is I shouldn't take everything by myself, that I should surrender it to God.   It's a very emotional movie. Despite the fact that I can't buy it, due to the triggers and it being too hard for me to handle, I would buy it, and watch it again.
